name: Tampon Tim
summary: Governor Tim Walz of Minnesota has come under fire from Republicans for a bill he signed into law that requires schools to provide free tampons and pads to students. The bill has been dubbed the "Tampon Bill" and has been criticized by some Republicans as an unnecessary government overreach. Despite the criticism, the bill has been praised by Democrats and advocates for menstrual equity, who argue that it is a necessary step to ensure that all students have access to essential hygiene products. The controversy has drawn national attention, with both Trump supporters and opponents of the bill using the term "Tampon Tim" to refer to Walz. Some political commentators have criticized the use of the term, arguing that it is an attempt to belittle and demean Walz and the issue of menstrual equity.

name: Billy Bean death
summary: Former Major League Baseball player and executive Billy Bean, who became the second openly gay ex-MLB player, passed away at the age of 60. Bean's career in baseball spanned decades, both on and off the field. After retiring as a player, he worked in the Commissioner's Office and dedicated his efforts to promoting diversity and inclusion in the sport. Bean's advocacy for LGBTQ rights and his work to create a more welcoming environment for all in baseball earned him widespread recognition and respect. His legacy as a trailblazer and leader in the fight for equality will continue to inspire future generations.

name: Lamecha Girma
summary: During the men's steeplechase final at the Paris Olympics, Ethiopian runner Lamecha Girma experienced a harrowing incident that resulted in him being stretchered off the track. Girma, who holds the world record in the event, tripped and fell, hitting his head hard on the track. The fall sent shockwaves through the crowd, and Girma was immediately attended to by medical personnel. He was taken to the hospital for further examination, while Moroccan runner Soufiane El Bakkali went on to retain his Olympic title. The incident has raised concerns about runner safety in the steeplechase, which involves jumping over hurdles and water barriers.

name: XRP
summary: Ripple Labs, the company behind the XRP cryptocurrency, has been ordered by a federal court to pay a $125 million penalty for improperly selling XRP tokens. The Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) had alleged that Ripple and its executives sold XRP as an unregistered security, raising over $1.3 billion in the process. Ripple has admitted to the improper sale of XRP but has denied that it was a security. The penalty is the largest ever imposed by the SEC for a digital asset offering and is a significant blow to Ripple's business. However, the news has been met with a surge in the price of XRP, with some investors seeing the penalty as a victory for Ripple and a sign of confidence in the company's future.

Despite the weather, fans and Bryan persevered, with Bryan expressing anger towards online criticism.

name: Walz
summary: The selection of Minnesota Governor Tim Walz as Vice President Kamala Harris's running mate has sparked both praise and criticism. Some view Walz as the ideal choice for the Democrats, citing his down-to-earth Midwestern persona and ability to connect with voters. Others have criticized his decision to retire from the military before the Iraq War, while others question his political ideology, labeling him as "dangerously liberal." Despite these criticisms, former President Trump has expressed satisfaction with Walz's handling of the George Floyd protests. Additionally, Lorne Michaels offered Walz the opportunity to portray himself on "SNL," but it was declined. These articles provide diverse perspectives on Walz as a political figure, highlighting both his strengths and areas of concern.

name: Earthquake
summary: Multiple earthquakes have recently struck California, Japan, and Tennessee, prompting warnings and advisories. Kern County, California, experienced a 5.2 magnitude earthquake, felt across the region and prompting warnings via mobile apps. Southern California was also affected by a 5.2 magnitude earthquake near Bakersfield, while Tennessee's Sevierville was shaken by a morning earthquake. Southern California has experienced over 200 earthquakes, raising questions about seismic activity. A powerful 7.1 magnitude earthquake off southern Japan triggered a tsunami advisory, while California was struck by a 5.3 magnitude earthquake centered near Bakersfield. Another 5.2 magnitude earthquake near Lamont shook Southern California, underscoring the recent increase in seismic activity in the region.

name: Cori Bush primary
summary: In a significant upset, Congress member Cori Bush, a prominent member of the progressive "Squad," was defeated in the Democratic primary for Missouri's 1st Congressional District by Wesley Bell. The defeat was attributed in part to a concerted campaign by pro-Israel groups, who poured funds into opposing Bush due to her support for the Boycott, Divestment, and Sanctions (BDS) movement. This victory marks the second time a member of the Squad has been unseated in a primary, following the defeat of Rashida Tlaib in Michigan. The result highlights the ongoing divide within the Democratic Party between progressive and moderate factions.

name: Cole Hocker
summary: American runner Cole Hocker defied all odds by securing an astonishing victory in the men's 1500-meter final at the Paris Olympics. Despite being a 21-to-1 underdog, Hocker displayed exceptional resilience and determination, coming from behind to claim the gold medal. His triumph marks a significant upset, surprising the highly favored competitors and setting a new Olympic record. Hocker's success adds to his growing list of accomplishments, which includes representing the United States at the collegiate level for the University of Oregon. This remarkable victory has made him a household name and cemented his place in the annals of American track and field history.
